		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<blockquote><hr>goid3 wrote:<br></p><DIV>Here's my point:</DIV><DIV>2. Tis saturday, at 7 am, estern time, the log in server went off, and at 11:30 pm, it was still off.</DIV><DIV> </DIV></p><DIV>What i mean is that :</DIV><DIV>2. You could easily afford another log in server (Back up system) in case the 1st one went off like this.</DIV><DIV> </DIV><br><hr></blockquote><br>Unfortunately, it is not that the login servers are down because of problems.  They are set to not allow logins because the game servers are still being patched.  Yes, the servers are up - but they need to be up in order to apply the patches and test.  Once the devs and testers (maybe the same folks) are reasonably satisfied that everything is working, they set the login server to allow people to log in to the game servers.  What really needs a change is the server status webpage - it needs to show what 'mode' the servers are in, rather than reflecting if they are simply up or down.  The point is that EQ, from the game servers to the web, could stand a bit of polishing once the bugs are stomped...
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							<p><font face="Tahoma"><br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=1126225"><br>Tyrelius Swifteagle</a></font></p><br><p>&nbsp;</p>
							</div>
								
