			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=TNZ&message.id=215755#M215755">188</a> of 205
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 511 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV>In my own gaming experience, I've left Everquest twice to play other games.&nbsp; First I left for SWG, then for EQ2, and I've come back both times.&nbsp; They simply did not have EQ's content.&nbsp; But then, what was so appealing about them?&nbsp; What elements of those games would make EQ more attractive?&nbsp; And what things would I like to see in EQ that have not been done?&nbsp; (At least, to my knowledge.)</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>SWG</DIV>
<DIV>1.&nbsp; Fantastic character creation.&nbsp; Characters were individually recognizable.</DIV>
<DIV>2.&nbsp; The Maker's Mark.&nbsp; Any tradeskilled item could be named by the maker and identified who made it.</DIV>
<DIV>3.&nbsp; Individual housing.&nbsp; Any player could place a structure and then decorate it with any object they had.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>4.&nbsp; Custom tradeskill items.&nbsp; Many tradeskilled items, such as clothing and weapons, had color choices or design options.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>EQ2</DIV>
<DIV>1. Updated graphics</DIV>
<DIV>2. Carefully studied player animations</DIV>
<DIV>3. Gorgeous outdoor zones</DIV>
<DIV>4.&nbsp;Guild accomplishments measured in purchasable items and faction.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>It should be noted, I didn't like the EQ2 characters at all.&nbsp; They had play-doh hair and strangely shaped, cartoonish bodies.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>EQ, simply put, has the appeal because of all of the content.&nbsp; At any given level, you have dozens of zones to play in, hundreds of quests to do, and thousands of weapons you can carry.&nbsp; How do you expand on that?&nbsp; My own humble thoughts, aside from adding features other games offer -</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Give us more rideable animals.&nbsp; Flying dragons or gryphons, maybe?&nbsp; Let us train them to make them faster or give them abilities.</DIV>
<DIV>Update character graphics.&nbsp; Any game is more appealing if it is prettier to play.</DIV>
<DIV>Update mob graphics.&nbsp; Why aren't all bears like those in Nedaria, for example?</DIV>
<DIV>Update city graphics.&nbsp; Qeynos and Felwithe - ugh.</DIV>
<DIV>Give us new ways to expand old characters.&nbsp; Maybe give us a secondary class, a subclass spell line, good/evil versions, quested or unlockable abilities, more epics, housing (as already mentioned), more face/hair choices if you aren't giving us new models, and new graphics for new clothing/armor.</DIV>
<DIV>Give us more new reasons to go to old zones.&nbsp; Put quest mobs in there, redesign them, upgrade the gear in so many of the old zones.&nbsp; They're just empty and useless as they are.</DIV>
<DIV>Put more amenities in the guild halls.&nbsp; Tradeskill vendors, instanced rooms, furniture, decor options, officer's hall, meeting place, mail room, and guild vendors.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>By all that's holy, make it so we can sit on chairs.</DIV>
<DIV>The character models are sorely outdated.&nbsp; Give us new, unique models that do not come from anywhere else.&nbsp; I guarantee, this will bring back a lot of your player base.</DIV>
<DIV>Add new gaming styles to old characters - such as leveling up through PVP, leveling up through tradeskilling, leveling up through training other players, or leveling up training mounts.&nbsp; These could be added to the character or added as a secondary forte.&nbsp; What if spellcrafting were&nbsp;a standalone or subclass?</DIV>
<DIV>Give us new methods of entertainment within the game.&nbsp; A real poker game, for example, or point to point races.&nbsp; Games within the game.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>That's all I can think of for now, but I'll add more as I meditate on it.&nbsp; Thank you for your time.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>	
		</td></tr>
